<br>
For example, I can run away from you, stop just outside of casting range to avoid getting hit, and then start hitting Ice Spear of Solist. By the time you (attempt to) hit me with a second Lure of Ice, my SIS will have already hit you, and I'll be running out of range again. Because SIS casts faster than Lure of Ice, I can get out of range safely before being hit. That's around maybe 200 damage to you right there, and I'm still at full life. At this point, you might decide to run back in range and cast SIS instead of Lure of Ice. Knowing you'd want to try this, I cunningly switch from SIS to Draught of Ice. Because Draught of Ice has a 3 second cast time, I'm a second ahead of you, meaning I can (once again) run out of range without getting hit. By now, my health bar is still full, and I've already put a dent in yours. If we go back to chain-casting lures, I will most likely win.<br>
<br>
Now that you've figured out my tactics, you might demand a rematch <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  You decide to mem Draught of Ice only, figuring you can run out of range if I (foolishly) try to use a slower spell. And if by chance I use the same tactics and we end up exchanging draughts, you have the greater chance of winning due to your HP gear. So we med, buff up, and mem our respective spells. At the beginning of the duel, you cast Draught of Ice from the edge of casting radius, expecting to run away and get a free hit. Instead of falling for it and trying to cast something, I immediately start running towards you. At this point, we have a sort of chase scenario: you're running away, but I'm hot on your tail about 50 feet behind you. If I stop to cast, I lose my distance advantage and you get out of range. If you decide to keep running, I eventually gain distance on you as you are forced to make turns around the zone edges. If you stop to cast, I immediately stop and hit Lure of Ice. After your draught hits me, you have 1.5 seconds to run 150 feet before my lure hits you (impossible). At this point, you've hit me with two draughts and I've hit you with one lure. I'm chasing you again, this time about 125 feet behind you. If you stop to cast draught at this point, I can still sneak in a lure just before you make it out of casting range. In other words, for every three draughts you hit me with, you get hit by two lures. If my resists are high enough, the fight is in my favor.<br>
<br>
If we're talking about BotB style arena dueling with a 30-second buffing period and no clickable items, there isn't much choice but to stand there and cast. But even then, it's still more complex than first lure wins. I might use the beginning of the round to dispel off your Manaskin and Manasink before switching to lures, giving me a huge HP advantage and thus allowing me to win the fight. If you're smart enough bury them under crap buffs before the duel, I'll mem two dispels at once, and cast one after the other in rapid succession. (This is how the BotB on Vallon was won.) <br>
<br>
Of course, all this is assuming you go into the duel with the mindset that standing there and chain-casting lures is all there is to wizard PvP. If you play it smart, bring golem wands, and use distance/casting radius to your advantage, you'll win 90% of the time.<br>
